      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-number">01 — About This Service</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">Before you call us — try the reset button.</h2>

        <p>We mean that. A significant number of garbage disposal calls we receive resolve with a simple reset. The small red or black button on the bottom of the unit under the sink is a thermal overload protector — when the disposal jams or overloads, it trips and cuts power to the motor. Press it firmly until you feel it click. If the disposal starts working, you don't need us. That's the honest answer.</p>

        <p>If the reset doesn't help — or if the disposal is humming without spinning, leaking under the sink, grinding poorly, or producing persistent odors — that's when we come in. Most garbage disposal issues are resolved in under an hour. Unjamming, seal replacement, motor diagnosis, drain clearing. We carry parts for InSinkErator, Moen, and Waste King units, which cover the majority of what's under LA sinks.</p>

        <p>The other honest thing we tell you: if your disposal is over 10 years old and the motor has failed, replacement is often the better financial decision. A new mid-range unit is $150–$250 and installation takes about an hour. We'll give you that assessment before writing any repair order.</p>

        <div class="tip-box">
          <div class="tip-label">🔧 Try This Before Calling</div>
          <p><strong>1.</strong> Cut power at the wall switch. Look underneath the unit for the reset button (small red/black button at the bottom). Press firmly until you feel it click, then restore power and test. <strong>2.</strong> If humming but not spinning: cut power, find the hex socket on the bottom of the unit, insert an Allen wrench and manually rotate the impeller to free the jam. These two steps resolve roughly 30% of disposal calls before anyone needs to come out.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="tip-safety">
          <div class="tip-label">⚠️ Safety — Never Reach In</div>
          <p>Never put your hand inside a garbage disposal — even when it's off. The impeller blades are sharp and the unit can be energized unexpectedly. If something is jammed and visible, use tongs or a wooden spoon handle. If you're not sure what's in there, cut power at the breaker before any inspection.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

