<!-- 04 PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02 — Common Problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians fix most often</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Humming But Not Spinning (Jammed)</h3>
        <p>The motor is running but the impeller plate is stuck. Could be a foreign object — a bottle cap, a small utensil, or a pit from a fruit. Cut power, use the Allen wrench in the hex socket on the bottom to manually rotate the impeller, then use tongs to remove the obstruction. If you can't free it, we can — jams are one of the most common calls we get.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Won't Turn On</h3>
        <p>Check the reset button first (bottom of unit). If reset doesn't help, check the circuit breaker. If both are fine, the wall switch, wiring connection, or motor has failed. We diagnose which — switch failures are inexpensive, motor failures on an old unit may make replacement the better choice.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Leaking Under the Sink</h3>
        <p>Three common leak sources: the sink flange at the top (worn putty or loose mounting), the dishwasher drain connection on the side, or the discharge drainpipe fitting at the bottom. A leak from the body of the unit itself means the housing is cracked — that requires replacement, not repair. We locate the exact source before doing any work.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Slow Drain or Not Grinding Well</h3>
        <p>A partially clogged drain, worn impeller blades, or food debris buildup in the grinding chamber all reduce grinding performance. Running cold water while operating the disposal and cleaning the chamber with ice cubes + salt helps maintain performance. If grinding is significantly reduced on a newer unit, we diagnose whether it's the disposal or the drain line.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Bad Smell</h3>
        <p>Food residue on the underside of the rubber splash guard (frequently overlooked) and buildup in the grinding chamber are the most common odor sources. Clean the splash guard's underside with a bottle brush. Ice + salt + citrus peels run through the disposal cleans the grinding components. Persistent odors after cleaning may indicate a drain blockage further down the line.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Overheating / Trips Reset Frequently</h3>
        <p>A disposal that trips its reset button repeatedly is either being jammed frequently (usually a usage issue), or the motor is beginning to fail. If you're running the disposal correctly — cold water, not overloading — and it still trips often, the motor is deteriorating. On a unit over 8 years old, this is a signal that replacement is coming.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 WHAT NOT TO PUT IN — LA ANGLE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — What Not to Put In</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">LA food culture and your garbage disposal</h2>
    <p class="lead">Los Angeles has farmers markets at every corner and a serious food culture — which means LA kitchens produce specific food waste that's particularly hard on disposals. These are the items we see causing the most jams and drain problems.</p>

    <div class="nope-block">
      <div class="nope-label">🚫 Keep These Out of Your Disposal</div>
      <h3>The LA kitchen list — avocado to artichoke</h3>
      <p>Garbage disposals are designed for light food scraps rinsed off plates — not for processing whole food items or fibrous produce. In an LA kitchen where avocado, citrus, artichokes, and stone fruits are daily staples, the disposal is one bad habit away from a jam or a clogged drain line.</p>

      <div class="nope-grid">
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Avocado pits</strong>Hard as a rock — will jam or crack the impeller</div>
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Artichoke leaves</strong>Fibrous and stringy, wraps around impeller shaft</div>
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Citrus peel (large amounts)</strong>Small amounts are fine; large quantities clog the drain</div>
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Banana peels</strong>Stringy, wraps around the motor shaft like a rope</div>
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Celery, asparagus</strong>Fibrous strings pass the blades and clog further down the drain</div>
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Potato &amp; yam peels</strong>Starchy — creates a paste that coats the grinding chamber</div>
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Stone fruit pits</strong>Apricot, cherry, peach pits — will crack or jam the impeller</div>
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Grease and cooking oil</strong>Congeals in drain lines — the most common cause of deeper clogs</div>
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Coffee grounds</strong>Fine and heavy — accumulates in the drain trap fast</div>
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Eggshells</strong>Membrane wraps; shells are sandy grit that coats pipes</div>
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Pasta and rice</strong>Expand with water, stick to grinding chamber and drain</div>
        <div class="nope-item"><strong>Bones, seeds</strong>Any hard item that can crack impeller or jam grinding plate</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 REPAIR VS REPLACE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — Repair or Replace?</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The honest guide — garbage disposals are one of the simpler decisions</h2>
    <p class="lead">Unlike most appliances, garbage disposals are inexpensive enough that the repair vs. replace calculation changes significantly based on age and failure type.</p>

    <div class="rvr-grid">
      <div class="rvr-card yes">
        <div class="rvr-badge badge-yes">✓ Usually Worth Repairing</div>
        <h3>Repair makes sense when...</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list yes">
          <li>Unit is under 6 years old</li>
          <li>It's a jam or foreign object — straightforward fix</li>
          <li>Leak is from a connection, not the body</li>
          <li>Reset button keeps tripping but unit is under 5 years old</li>
          <li>You have a premium model (InSinkErator Evolution series)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rvr-card no">
        <div class="rvr-badge badge-no">✗ Replace often makes more sense when...</div>
        <h3>Replacement makes sense when...</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list no">
          <li>Unit is over 10 years old and motor has failed</li>
          <li>Leak is from the housing body (it's cracked — not repairable)</li>
          <li>Reset trips frequently and unit is aging</li>
          <li>Repair cost approaches or exceeds new unit cost</li>
          <li>You're already replacing the sink or dishwasher</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p style="margin-top:20px; font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--muted); line-height:1.65;">We give you this assessment during the diagnostic. A new mid-range InSinkErator runs $150–$250 and installation takes about an hour. If replacement makes more sense, we'll tell you — and we can install the new unit the same visit if you'd like.</p>
  </div>
</section>

