<!-- 08 RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Silver Lake · InSinkErator Evolution Excel</div>
        <h3>"Humming loudly but won't spin — has been like this since last night"</h3>
        <p>An apricot pit had gotten past the rubber splash guard and lodged between the impeller and the grinding ring. The pit was visible with a flashlight but couldn't be reached safely with fingers. The motor had been humming all evening — customer heard it but didn't realize what it was until the next morning when the disposal wouldn't work.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Cut power at the wall switch. Used Allen wrench to manually rock the impeller, which freed the pit partway. Extracted with needle-nose pliers. Tested full rotation, confirmed no impeller damage. Advised customer on what stone fruits do to disposals — they'd been putting pitted fruit directly in for years. 20-minute call.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">West Hollywood · InSinkErator Badger 5</div>
        <h3>"Water dripping under the sink — cabinet floor is wet"</h3>
        <p>Leak from the sink flange — the mounting assembly that seals the disposal to the sink drain opening. The plumber's putty had dried out and shrunk over 9 years, creating a gap where water could seep through during operation. The dripping was slow enough that it had soaked the cabinet floor without the customer noticing for several weeks.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Loosened the mounting assembly, cleaned old putty from the sink flange and drain opening, repacked with fresh plumber's putty, reassembled and retightened. Ran disposal for 5 minutes with water flow — no drip confirmed. Also tightened the dishwasher drain connection which had slight play. Cabinet floor dry before leaving.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Pasadena · Moen GX Series</div>
        <h3>"Won't turn on at all — tried the reset button, nothing"</h3>
        <p>Failed wall switch — the switch controlling the disposal had burned out internally. With the switch failed open, no power was reaching the disposal regardless of the reset button state. Easy to diagnose by bypassing the switch with a meter — the disposal ran fine when powered directly, confirming the switch was the fault.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced wall switch with a new standard single-pole switch. Verified disposal operation through several on/off cycles. Also noticed the drain rubber gasket at the dishwasher connection was slightly deteriorated — replaced as preventive maintenance while there. 30-minute repair including parts.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Culver City · InSinkErator 9-Year-Old Unit</div>
        <h3>"Grinding gets weaker every month — starting to back up"</h3>
        <p>Nine-year-old disposal with worn impeller blades and partially clogged drain line from grease accumulation. The disposal was still functional but grinding at about 60% of original effectiveness. Repair assessment: motor was intact but impellers were not replaceable as a standalone part on this model. New unit cost vs. repair cost: not worth repairing.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Gave customer honest recommendation: replacement. Installed customer-supplied InSinkErator Evolution 200 — a significant upgrade from the old Badger 5. Cleared the drain line with a drain snake before connecting the new unit. Disposed of old unit. Customer noted the new disposal is dramatically quieter than the old one — Evolution series has sound insulation the Badger series doesn't.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

