<!-- 10 FAQ -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">08 — Frequently Asked Questions</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Garbage disposal repair — what people ask us</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How much does garbage disposal repair cost in Los Angeles?</h3>
        <p>Our diagnostic fee is $89, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most repairs run between $89 and $200. Unjamming and minor leak repairs are toward the lower end. Motor failure on an older unit may cost more than a new unit — we give you a repair vs. replace assessment upfront.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My garbage disposal is humming but not spinning — what's wrong?</h3>
        <p>Something is jammed. Cut power, find the hex socket on the bottom of the unit, insert an Allen wrench and manually rotate the impeller to free the jam, then use tongs to remove the obstruction. If you can't free it, we can — most jams are resolved in 15–20 minutes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My garbage disposal won't turn on at all — is it broken?</h3>
        <p>Check the reset button first — small red or black button at the bottom of the unit. Press firmly until it clicks. Also check the circuit breaker. If neither resolves it, the wall switch, wiring, or motor has failed — call us.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Should I repair or replace my garbage disposal?</h3>
        <p>Disposals last 8–12 years. Under 6 years old — repair almost always makes sense. Over 10 years with a failed motor — replacement is often the better financial decision. A new mid-range InSinkErator is $150–$250 and installation takes about an hour. If the housing body is cracked and leaking, replacement is required. We give you this assessment before writing any repair order.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My disposal smells bad even after running it — how do I fix that?</h3>
        <p>The rubber splash guard's underside (often overlooked) and the grinding chamber are the most common odor sources. Clean the splash guard with a bottle brush. Run ice cubes + salt + citrus peels through the disposal. If odor persists, there may be a drain blockage further down the line.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do you install new garbage disposals?</h3>
        <p>Yes. We install units you supply or supply and install ourselves. Installation includes all plumbing and electrical connections and testing for leaks before we leave. If you're replacing an older unit, we can advise on which model makes sense for your household size and usage.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What does the 90-day warranty cover on garbage disposal repairs?</h3>
        <p>Every repair we complete carries a 90-day warranty on both parts and labor. If the same issue returns within that window, we come back at no charge. That's in writing before we leave.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

